                    "longNarrative": "From Bank Logic to User Logic: Redesigning a Loan Request Flow That Increased Conversion from <10% to ~80%\n\nShort summary\n\nAt Nexus, a peer-to-peer lending marketplace connecting SME borrowers with retail investors, I worked on redesigning the company loan request flow. The original process followed a bank-like model: before a business could even be evaluated, it had to provide a heavy set of supporting documents for credit analysis. This created major friction and kept request conversion below 10%. I proposed inverting the logic: instead of demanding proof upfront, we would trust applicantsâ€™ declared information, enrich it with third-party data sources, and only request documents after conditional approval and borrower acceptance. This shift dramatically increased conversion to roughly 80% and created a much more user-centered alternative to the traditional banking experience.\n\nContext\n\nNexus operated as a peer-to-peer lending marketplace. On one side were small and medium-sized businesses looking for loans, often because traditional banks either under-served them or offered terms that were too expensive. On the other side were retail investors who collectively funded those loans as an investment product.\n\nThe loan request flow sat at a critical point in the marketplace: if businesses dropped before completing an application, the platform lost qualified demand before risk assessment even began. That made the application experience not only a UX problem, but also a core business problem.\n\nThe problem\n\nThe original application process mirrored the logic used by banks. Businesses were asked to provide a large volume of documents early in the journey, before there was any indication that a loan would actually be approved.\n\nThis created several problems:\n\nHigh effort upfront: SME owners had to gather and submit multiple documents before receiving any signal that the process was worth their time.\nLow motivation: Because Nexus was not a traditional bank brand, borrowers had less reason to tolerate heavy administrative burden at the start.\nPoor conversion: Loan request conversion was below 10%.\nMisaligned sequencing: The process optimized for institutional certainty too early, instead of for user momentum.\n\nThe standard logic in financial services was clear: ask for documents first, analyze later. But that logic had been inherited from banks rather than designed around the actual needs and behavior of our users.\n\nKey insight\n\nThe breakthrough was recognizing that banks use upfront documents for two different purposes at once:\n\nto gather data for credit analysis\nto filter for seriousness, intent, and compliance\n\nThose two jobs did not necessarily need to happen at the same moment.\n\nI proposed separating them.\n\nInstead of requiring proof before any value was returned to the borrower, we could:\n\ncollect easy-to-provide information first\nenrich and validate risk signals through external data sources\nmake a preliminary decision\nonly then request documentary proof as part of final compliance and verification\n\nThat would reduce friction without abandoning control.\n\nMy role\n\nI proposed the change in application logic and helped shape the new experience around a user-first sequence rather than a bank-first sequence. The work required aligning product thinking with credit, compliance, and data realities, since the challenge was not just simplifying an interface but redesigning the logic of how risk evaluation entered the journey.\n\nConstraints\n\nThis was not a simple form simplification project. We had to work within real operational constraints:\n\nfinancial risk could not be ignored\ncompliance still required proof of revenue, cash flow, and business legitimacy\nborrowers needed to authorize checks on credit history and related records\nthe company had lower default trust than incumbent banks\nthe process still had to protect investors on the other side of the marketplace\n\nThe solution therefore had to reduce user burden without weakening risk controls.\n\nThe solution\n\nWe redesigned the loan request flow around progressive commitment.\n\n1. We removed document upload from the start of the application\n\nInstead of asking businesses to gather a large set of files upfront, we began with information they could provide quickly and easily.\n\n2. We asked for structured self-reported business data\n\nApplicants entered information such as company identity, ownership, and starting revenue, along with other details needed to assess the request.\n\n3. We used external data providers to enrich the application\n\nUsing the company tax ID and the tax IDs of associated owners and stakeholders, we mapped relevant entities and pulled available signals from external sources.\n\n4. We requested permission to access formal credit records\n\nApplicants authorized checks tied to central banking and credit history systems, allowing us to evaluate risk without requiring immediate document submission.\n\n5. We moved proof documents to the post-approval stage\n\nOnly after a loan was conditionally approvedâ€”and the borrower chose to proceedâ€”did we ask for documentary evidence to verify reported revenue, cash flow, and compliance details.\n\nIn other words, we moved from â€œprove first, maybe receive value laterâ€ to â€œreceive a serious evaluation first, then verify before completion.â€\n\nOutcome\n\nThe change produced a major increase in conversion.\n\nLoan request conversion increased from under 10% to roughly 80%\nPositive progression into credit analysis rose to over 50%, based on my recollection\nSome applicants were still rejected later, either because their declared information did not support approval or because documentation failed final verification\nEven with those downstream losses, the overall journey performed far better than the original bank-like model\n\nThe result was not just a more efficient funnel. It was a better-designed business experience that matched the expectations and constraints of SME owners.\n\nWhy this worked\n\nThis redesign worked because it attacked the real source of friction: premature burden.\n\nSME borrowers were willing to provide information, but asking them to compile proof documents before they knew whether the opportunity was real imposed too much cost too early. By changing the sequence, we preserved trust and momentum.\n\nIt also reinforced the brand promise. Instead of behaving like a smaller copy of a bank, Nexus behaved like a different kind of financial serviceâ€”faster, more modern, and more aligned with the userâ€™s reality.\n\nMost importantly, the project showed that in regulated products, innovation does not always come from removing controls. Sometimes it comes from placing controls at the right moment in the journey.\n\nWhat I learned\n\nThis case taught me that some of the strongest product opportunities come from questioning process assumptions that everyone treats as fixed.\n\nIn this case, the opportunity was not just â€œmake the form easier.â€ It was to ask a deeper question:\n\nWhy are we asking for proof at this stage at all?\n\nOnce that assumption was challenged, we were able to redesign the experience around user commitment, not institutional habit. The result improved conversion, preserved necessary safeguards, and helped define a more differentiated product experience."
